今年特にお世話になったモデルさんへひと言感謝を述べるシリーズ。二人目は日菜さん。圧倒的な透明感と、笑ったときの優しさが伝わってくる表情、そして撮影に真剣に取り組む姿勢が印象的な素敵なモデル。それが佐咲日菜さんのイメージです。あと、声がすっっごく素敵。
.
実はめちゃくちゃ前から知ってたのに自分が声をかける勇気がなく、撮影に至るまで1年以上かかってたりします笑
.
そんな日菜さんとの撮影は彼女が徹夜明けだったこともあり最後の方寝落ちしかかってたのが微笑ましく思い出されます。ただ実際の撮影中は驚かされることが多々ありました。特に記憶に残っているのは、スッとカメラを向けた瞬間の目の色の変わり方、被写体としてその世界観に入っていく集中力は類を見ず、自分もぐいぐい引っ張っていってもらいました。
.
そんな日菜さんは最近MVやドラマなどの映像作品への出演へ注力されているので、もしよろしければ皆さんもフォロー、応援よろしくお願いします🥳
.
最後に。日菜さん、今年初撮影が出来てとても楽しかったです。でも、本音を言うとまだまだ日菜さんと撮りたいです！満足してません！(良い意味で！)なので来年また機会いただけたら嬉しいです🥺🙏それまで自分も腕を磨いて待ってます。今年残りも健康に気をつけてお過ごし下さい。そして、良いお年を！🎍

UX in Japan
​​Here are some small designs I found in Japan that make many people’s life more convenient. But you might not notice before. ​​
​​
​​​🥛​Milk Box
​​
​​The chip on the beverage packaging means the beverage is pure milk. ​​
​​​🍺​Beer
​​
​​The beer in Japan has braille on top of the can. The braille usually says "alcohol," but sometimes it spells out the manufacture's name.
​​
​​​🚆​Metro Card - Suica
​​
​​On the metro card, there’s a chip on one side to indicate it’s the front of the card ​​
​​​🥤​Vending machine
​​
​​Most of the functions are in the lower section of the vending machine
​​
​​​🍯​Dressing package from Kewpie
​​
​​My first time saw this packaging I was amazed. ​​You simply need to squeeze the dressing using one hand. Clean and simple.
​​
​​​💁‍♀️​Shampoo vs hair conditioner
​​
​​To tell from shampoo and conditioner, look at the top of the knot and the side of the bottle. ​​
​​​📦​Yamato Transport Delivery Notice
​​
​​On the ‘attempted delivery notice’, there is a cat ear shape of cut off. So the blind people can tell there was a delivery by touching cat ears shape the edge.
​​ ​​Do you see these design in your life?
​​Share in the comments!
​​​😉​
​​I hope enjoy this post! Next time I’d like to share some of the smart packaging in Japan.​🔖​Share with a friend if you like this post :)

T-shaped skills is one of the most essential concepts, especially in the Product Design industry. Being aware of that, you can design your professional path and consiously choose which skills do you need to acquire.

How to take advantage of the 2 different dimensions of skills to grow professionally and become indispensable?

There are 2 major dimentions of skills: 1/ Specialist
2/ Generalist

By combination of these 2, you can become a T-skilled designer, and become a profile that most of the companies are looking for🔥

If you will spend 10+ years in the industry, at some point you might achieve the proficiency in many different aspects and become the "UX Unicorn". If you will do so - let me know! 😅

It's essential to understand clients or the employer's perspective on the two dimensions of skills.

By the nature of work and challenges, startups often lean towards people that are good at many different aspects, while big corporation looks for experts. It’s not a rule, though, so always try to verify who they are looking for.

How to find You Career Path?

While some people prefer to be in the middle of everything (i.e., Product Managers or Product Owners), other love spending all day long in Figma, AE, or coding. By the end of the day, there are good or wrong answers — it’s all about you and where do you want to be in a few years. Choose wisely!

from @lubosvolkov -  7 Awesome Tips How to Design Better Apps 🔥
_________
There are almost 2.2 million applications in the Appstore … But creating a great mobile experience takes a lot of practice ... Today we are going to look into actionable tips on how to design better applications … Let’s do that.
_________
🧐 Why you should read this post?
____
Almost every single company has a native mobile experience now ... However, with the scale, we often keen to forget about the very little things which can make the experience better for the end-users ... Do you remember the last time when you downloaded the new app and uninstalled that in few minutes? ... Today you will learn how to create better app experiences.
.
What you will find in the post?
____
1️⃣ Try to avoid onboarding tours
2️⃣ Utilize existing patterns
3️⃣ Add labels for icons
4️⃣ Design for big thumbs
5️⃣ Optimize push notifications
6️⃣ Battery life is affected by design
7️⃣ Set a primary goal for the screen
8️⃣ (Secret) Summary
.
🤯 Key takeaways
____
Always focus on the end-user and their goal within the screen or application ... Try to remove unnecessary things until you will get the minimum what the user needs ... Try to think about small details such as touch area or notifications ... Lastly, try to use existing and established patterns if possible without limiting the innovation. 
_________
➡️ Which one is your favorite tip? Let me know the number in the comments below.

How to start in UX/UI?
In the past weeks, I got asked this question a lot! I wasn't able to answer all of them, so I decided to prepare a post that answers this question from my perspective. Because of the limited space, I wasn't able to put everytjing in it. This is a subject you can talk about for hours, so if you have any additional questions, make sure to ask them in comments!
.
When it comest to the process you can sum it up in few steps:
1️⃣Understand the domain (UX & UI)
2️⃣Decide where to start (UX or UI? you won't be able to do both at first!) 3️⃣Learn the process & methods
4️⃣Learn basic tools
5️⃣Practice
6️⃣When you already have the basics in place, learned the theory, tools and practised, now is the time to look for a mentor!
.
In the post I mentioned "UX for Freelancers" course by @Anfisign - make sure to check it out!

-

You got your first job as a UX Designer. That's great! But what awaits you along your career? These are the roles and levels a UX Designer go through as they gather experience and start to specialise more and more.
-
It's crucial to note that the more advanced roles doesn’t mean better and more important! You can become a great and valuable UX Designer and never specialize in a certain role. This is more of a list of roles that are currently looked for in bigger companies, but you can also become a very well prepared all-rounder, for example if you’re working on your own as a freelancer.

5️⃣ Graphic #Design 🖼️ #Trends of 2020
•
1. #3D depth and realism 🎲
The 3D trend reached its peak in 2019 and it certainly won’t fade away so quickly. Thanks to the opportunities of modern technology and software capabilities, in 2020, we will keep seeing more awesome 3D graphic design compositions.
•
2. Going monochrome 📚
Lately, we’ve been seeing a tendency of graphic and web designers using a monochromatic color effect on pictures. Remember the duotone craze from graphic design trends 2017️⃣? It turns out, the trend has now evolved into even a more simplified version.
•
3. Line art 🎨
The trend of outline typography and elements which have been quite mass during 2018 and 2019 is now evolving into fully illustrated and animated line art patterns and designs.
•
4. Image and text masking 🖼️
Image and text masking isn’t a new technique to the design world but it still looks quite modern in 2020.
•
5. #Typography craze 💯
In order to create more innovative and modern compositions, designers are playing with typography big time. This trend is expected to flourish in 2️⃣0️⃣2️⃣0️⃣. Figuratively and literally!

-
Author: @lubosvolkov
-
Published by: @ui_gradient

________
Buttons are essential part of almost every user interface … In today's post we are going to look at some visual examples and actionable tips how to improve your buttons … Let’s do that.
________
🧐 Why are buttons so important?
__
Buttons are allowing users to perform actions or complete the task … They are so essential part of every interface that we often forget how important they actually are … If they are done right they can improve overall user experience … Or eventually generate more revenue for the business.
.
What you will find in the post?
__
1️⃣ Buttons have voice and tone
2️⃣ Create proper button hierarchy 
3️⃣ Provide visual feedback 
4️⃣ Increase touch and click area
5️⃣ Give buttons breathing space
6️⃣ Use descriptive labels 
7️⃣ Focus on accessibility
8️⃣ Valuable articles, softwares & books
.
🤯 Key takeaways
__
Buttons are key elements of every interface … You should craft them with attention to details such as padding, font size or accessibility … Try to also think about text labels on the buttons … Lastly do not be afraid to experiment with motion and transform button based on the state or action.

Happy Sunday everyone!⁣ After sharing my morning routine last week, many of you asked about what I do at night.⁣
⁣
To feed your curiosity, here it is. ⁣
⁣
I use to work from 6AM till 9PM. However that lifestyle was toxic and led me to burning out in 2014. ⁣
⁣
That was definitely one of the most darkest times in my life. Losing direction and motivation left me feeling lost and alone. ⁣
⁣
Now a days I will try not to bring work home. I work extremely hard from 6AM to 6PM. With no excuses, I will stop work on the dot. ⁣
⁣
I will also avoid thinking about work during the night, by focusing on other things I enjoy.⁣

Can you guys guess what I’m getting ready for?🤔

I spent the first 3 years of my ‘design career’ hustling on 99designs, design contests on DigitalPoint and Sitepoint and working on random design jobs from referrals.⁣
⁣
I wasn’t progressing.⁣
⁣
But I learnt you can only work smart AFTER you work hard. ⁣
⁣
Realising it wasn’t getting anywhere, I focused on launching a unique portfolio design.⁣ Submitted it to all the design galleries.⁣
⁣
Got featured on FWA, CSS Mania and many other galleries.⁣
⁣
Got my work in-front of many prospective clients.⁣
⁣
They reached out to me looking to get work done, meaning they were ‘qualified leads’ already.⁣
⁣
Winning these clients were much easier!⁣
⁣
From a very early stage in my freelance career, I experienced the power of ‘inbound marketing’. Ever since then I focused on strengthening my personal brand. ⁣
⁣
As you can see, I receive well over 20 qualified leads now.⁣
⁣
There is no secret to this.⁣
⁣
FORMULA: WORK HARD > WORK SMART > WORK CONSISTENTLY = SUCCESS⁣

Doctors will diagnose your symptoms before recommending a solution.⁣
Vets will diagnose your pet’s problems before recommending a solution.⁣
Lawyers will understand your situation before suggesting next steps.⁣ Why would designers agree to a scope before assessing the situation? ⁣
⁣
We shouldn’t.⁣
⁣
Whenever a client approaches you thinking they know what they need, take a step back and take a deep breathe in.⁣
⁣
Realise, they are not the experts.⁣ As a service provider, we don’t only provide output but we also need to understand and diagnose problems to be able to produce impactful outcomes.⁣
⁣
1. Ask questions.⁣
2. Understand the client’s situation.⁣
3. Probe them about what problems they are facing.  Let me know in the comments below, if this was useful to you!⁣

I’ve been receiving a lot of questions about landing a job without ‘experience’. ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
The reality is, unless you’re a bit of a unicorn designer, you’re not going to land the perfect job as a junior.⁣⁣
⁣⁣
This post assumes that you’re already giving your career your best shot. Launching side projects and freelancing whenever you can. Building experience wherever possible. ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
When you’re applying for your first job, no one wants to hire someone with zero experience. That’s the reality we live in. ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
So lower your expectations. ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
The job might not be exactly what you’re looking for, but it’s still something.⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Something is better than nothing.⁣⁣
⁣⁣
No one is telling you to stay there forever.⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Stick around for 6, 12 or 24 months. Learn everything you can.⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Once you plateau, move on. But this time you’ll already have experience under your belt, making your application process 2x easier.⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Just remember, every new job you land becomes easier and easier. ⁣⁣

.

Basically a 30,000 ft view of the website and the navigation as a whole. Once that's approved...
.
Step 3 - WIREFRAME
Zooming in to single pages to look at the content on that page and to figure out the flow that is going to best help the user accomplish those goals with as few steps as possible.
.
Step 4 - VISUAL DESIGN
How the site looks; aesthetics, buttons, colors, type, spacing and layout.
.
Step 5 - DEVELOPMENT
Create the website using code so that it can live online.

Resharing this post of mine with the concept proposed by Jesse James Garrett as I believe that it’s a valuable representation to popularize - mostly because too often design conversation happen on the surface level instead of going deeper into the important questions and problems that design needs to solve. •

Plus, this representation perfectly goes to show that UX design is so much more than visual design, despite the fact that in many spaces in the design industry it is still regarded as merely “screen making” or the pretty layer you add after other roles than the design ones decide the solution. •

Have you encountered this kind of role misunderstanding in your professional collaborations? •

I’ve always stressed this. Great designers don’t just design.⁣
-⁣
They solve customer and business problems. For one to do so effectively, they need to understand all the moving parts that come into play.⁣
-⁣
There are 3 main stages when it comes to the business life cycle.⁣
-⁣
PRE-VALIDATION: An idea that is floating around. The main focus is to launch a MVP as soon as possible to test the market. ⁣
PRODUCT MARKET FIT: People show interest. The idea has been launched and you have customers who ‘repeatedly’ pay you for the value. ⁣
SCALE: Your product has proven to retain users, customers are passing on the good word about your service and the businesses core focus is to scale their acquisition channels.⁣
-⁣
Problems and challenges customers and businesses face during these stages are significantly different. Designers need to adapt to these situations and empathise effectively. ⁣
-⁣
Here are 5 non-design books to help you build a better understanding of other relevant disciplines:⁣
-⁣
1. The Lean Startup: Truly understand how fast growing tech startups are now building products. Lean and extremely outcomes driven.⁣
2. Made to Stick: Learn how and why some brands and marketing ideas really stick and become viral.⁣
3. Good to Great: Understand the fundamental catalysts that drive a business to go from ‘good’ to ‘great’.⁣
4. Cross the Chasm: Technology adoption is broken up into 5 segments, Innovators, Early adopters, Early Majority, Late Majority and Laggards. Learn what it takes for a product to penetrate the wider audience in today’s world.⁣
5. Emotional intelligence (Harvard business review): In the end it doesn’t matter how great we are at problem solving, if people don’t enjoy working with us it means nothing. Understand what it means to have high EQ. This book is a great overview on the impact of EQ on job performance, leadership potential, entrepreneurship, and employability.⁣
-⁣⁣⁣ ⁣⁣⁣⁣

When I started my company, Design Cuts, we invested an afternoon to define our audience. One of the smartest decisions we could have made.
-
We drew a figure, and called him 'Timmy'. We started by defining 'hard metrics'. Like what Timmy did for a living. How much he earned. What skills he had. What software he used.
-
We took the time to define 'soft metrics'. What did Timmy get excited about? What did Timmy find funny? What hobbies did he have? What was his personality like? This may sound trivial, but combined, they create a rich audience persona.
-
Imagine we got it wrong and created 'Corporate Carl'. A ruthless career climber, chasing materialistic pursuits. He's eats at fancy restaurants and drinks at fancy bars. He's not very empathetic. He's kind of a dick!
-
Instead, we knew our audience persona was: A full time creative. Had enough disposable income to invest in assets to help their work. Empathetic. Resistant to traditional corporate culture. Family orientated. Super geeky about design. Drank a lot of coffee. Slightly geeky. Engaged in creative pursuits outside of design. And hundreds of other traits!
-
It may sound abitrary, and to an extent it is, but this is not about exact science, it's about direction. Not every audience member mapped to this profile, but it was surprising how we attracted people in those early days who were very similar to it. The outcome? When we posted funny designer memes about coffee, they blew up! When we shared our geeky traits and family values, our audience seriously connected. When we talk about the trials and tribulations of being a full-time designer, people feel like we're in their heads.
-
The big takeaway. Creating a good audience persona will: -
Better inform your marketing efforts
-
Make content creation easier
-
Make copywriting easier
-
Make your audience feel understood
-
Create a deeper bond with your audience
-
Let me know in the comments: what do you know about YOUR audience?

How to become a UX designer in 1 year! Tips by @uxlinks.
.
UX is a skilled and multi-disciplined area. It’s worth spending some time to understand what it is and the variety of roles.
.
You will find that you gravitate towards an area that compliments your current skills or perhaps an area that you find interesting.
.
Great UX traits:
Passion for how things work.
Empathy for users’ frustrations.
Curiosity to keep learning.
Micro and macro thinking. Look at the detail and the bigger picture.
Great communication to present and sell your designs to stakeholders.
Flexibility/adaptability. Tech projects are constantly changing.
Being humble. UX is a team effort.
.
Online resources:
There are so many amazing online resouces for UX. Depending on how you like to learn, you may prefer video or audio or even written material.
Whichever you choose, be consistent.
Devote time each day to learning.

User Experience design framework adapted for the Pro Membership. A while back we had Associate Director @thisisnicolej share a UX design process on the show. Go watch it now if you haven’t already.

I think the framework she used was super simple and brilliant. It’s boiled down to 3 prompts: Tasks, Gaps, Opportunities. This can be used for anything. It says, get to know me. Understand my wants and needs. Find areas where I’m falling short. Then, solve my problems.

In this post, I use it to look at how we might improve the user experience for the Pro Group.

It’s a little dense but I hope the example sparks ideas in you. Give it a try and see what you come up with. If you’re a UX expert feel free to give me feedback on anything I missed or make suggestions. Thanks.

How to get things done when you are ready to start. If you haven’t done so, check out post 1 & 2 on goal setting, making check lists and how to use the impact/effort graph. Sometimes I get anxious when I feel like I have too many things to do. Not quite full on panic attack but shortness of breath.

I tell myself to relax and get a checklist going. This eases my mind and gives me something to focus on. Each time I hit my target, I cross it off my list and it feels amazing. You can actually see your own progress.

I’ve included a scaffolding exercise that might help you take big tasks and chop them down to bite sized pieces. This works for just about anything. 3-5 steps are best. Give it a try and let me know what you think.

Fitt’s Law - Paul Fitts⁣
Zeigarnik Effect - Bluma Wulfovna Zeigarnik⁣
Serial Position Effect - Herman Ebbinghaus⁣
Law of Common Region - Gestalt Psychology⁣
Law of Proximity - Gestalt Psychology⁣

Want to make more money doing what you do? Try using Price Anchors. The principle is that we all rely too much on the first piece of information that we receive. So when it comes to pricing, anchor high. Say a big number first. This number is usually considerably higher than the number you intend to say.

Here’s an example of how we use it. I will often tell clients that our minimum level of engagement is $100k. This is regardless of what the task is.

Once we start talking about their goals, motivations and determine what they need, they have been conditioned to think it will cost around 100k. So any number I say that is around $100k will seem very reasonable.

Conversely if the client says they only have $30k before I have the opportunity to bring up the budget, now, I’m stuck thinking about a number that’s not too far away from $30k. See how anchors work? Give it a try. When you’re successful, just remember where you learned this from.

If you’re not confident talking about money, I recommend using precise numbers. The client will think you really put thought into it. When you become more confident use round numbers for the exact opposite reason. It says to the client “it’s the price if you want to me.” They can’t detect a formula to negotiate against.

If you want more, I’ll be doing workshops on Pricing Strategies. Check the last slide for dates. Check the Futur’s FB page for more info.

Есть такие места, от которых эмоции внутри просто разрывают грудную клетку, на которые смотришь и хочется плакать от переполняющей тебя красоты, которые наполняют тебя жизненной энергией и умиротворением. В эти места хочется возвращаться, чтобы вновь испытать этот трепет. Кастанеда говорит, что это называется «положительным местом силы» (бывают и отрицательные - забирающие энергию). И вот эти положительные места силы делятся на пять групп. Курайская степь для меня, скорее всего, это вторая группа «мест силы» - та, которая активирует какую-либо энергоструктуру организма (чакру, меридиан и др) и создаёт через это полезную активацию эмоционально-волевой или интеллектуальной функций организма. Если проще - я там счастлив и умиротворён как буддийский монах, хоть я и не знаю насколько они умиротворены 🧘🏼‍♂️

How to become a UX designer in 1 year!
-
By: @uxlinks
-
UX is a skilled and multi-disciplined area.  It’s worth spending some time to understand what it is and the variety of roles.
-
You will find that you gravitate towards an area that compliments your current skills or perhaps an area that you find interesting.
-
Great UX traits:
Passion for how things work.
Empathy for users’ frustrations.
Curiosity to keep learning.
Micro and macro thinking.  Look at the detail and the bigger picture.
Great communication to present and sell your designs to stakeholders.
Flexibility/adaptability. Tech projects are constantly changing.
Being humble. UX is a team effort.
-
Online resources:
There are so many amazing online resouces for UX. Depending on how you like to learn, you may prefer video or audio or even written material.
Whichever you choose, be consistent.
Devote time each day to learning.

So we see these terms floating about on job boards, bios, descriptions, etc. you name it. Everyone is talking about being a product designer, ux designer, or any other of the hot titles focused around design
-
But what the heck is the difference?
-
Product Designers - A Product Designer, according to uxdesign.cc, Design will not be just about users. It will also be about the business. As Product Designers, we must drive product solutions that service the goals of both the users and the company
-
Product Designers are well-versed in many areas and generally oversee the entire lifecycle of a product
-
Think UX Designer meets Product Manager
-
UX Designer - A UX Designer is someone who makes products easy to use. They incorporate user research, understand user behavior, and the target market, and craft solutions for those specific use cases
-
In short, UX Designers are responsible for crafting intuitive and engaging experiences

The power of White Space in UI design -
By: @_ayushjangra_
-
“Let’s reduce the empty space a little so that we present the user with more content at once.” - The Client
-
How many of you have heard this line from your clients.
-
Clients usually argue and push the tendency that we should condense the content by reducing the negative space with the idea that we are presenting the user with more valuable content at once. Showing more content in one view doesn’t necessarily accomplish that. That is the myth of “less scrolling”. By giving the UI elements more space, we, as designers, contribute to the emotional aspect of the user experience. We add more breathing space in the UI and relax the overall interaction of the user’s experience with the UI.
-
Spacing makes the UI breathe and the user feels more comfortable exploring it.
-
Did you guys had any such experience where you had to explain the importance of white space and convince the client to keep that negative space, let me know in the comments below!
-

—
❗Why is it important to use the latest industry standards?
1⃣ Standards are like a language for designers, using different tools is like communicating via different languages.
2⃣ Industry standards sometimes are required by companies
3⃣ Using the latest standards means you are up to date.
4⃣ They are used by a wider community so collaborations are way easier.
5⃣ Industry standard tools usually get more updates and better support.
—
—
❗When is the best time to make the switch?
1⃣ You see a better potential on the other tool.
2⃣ You see big companies making the switch.
3⃣ You feel like the tool you are using is falling behind with features.

Here are some new tips made by our own @bumble_bee_11 e at @bazen.agency about adding depth to a design.
-
Adding a sense of depth to a design can make that design seem more realistic and increase visual interest.
-
Since we are 3-dimensional beigns, the lack of one dimension on screen means our compositions appear less than lifelike.
-
Adding back the illusion of the missing dimension will add back a sense of reality.
-

App or Website: which to build first?
-
Should you build an app or website first for your startup?
-
This question comes up a lot in the startup world, and there's reasons why I would lean one way over the other in various circumstances. Below I'll give you the pros and cons for going with web over app and vice versa. - 
Website pros:
1. Faster (cheaper) to implement
2. Compatibility
3. Search Engine Optimization
-
Website cons:
1. No offline access
2. Native device limitations
3. Often a clunkier user experience -
App pros:
1. Richer User Experience
2. Native features 
3. Performance
4. Offline access
-
App cons:
1. Development costs
2. Time intensive
3. Maintenance and updates
-
In short, do your research. -

Quick—is a logo a brand?

A brand is a person’s gut feeling about a product, service or organization. It’s not what you say it is. It’s what they say it is.

@marty_neumeier has a series of books on branding and they are simply brilliant. Each book is so well written in presenting a clear and concise case for what branding is. 
Where appropriate, he includes thoughtful and easy to understand illustrations. 
If you use the word “brand” or “branding”, I highly suggest you deepen your understanding of the word before you write your next post or present to a prospective client.

Chair/Sofa set for interior-design-loving introverts!
-
The Capsule by @katerynasokolova, with its soft felt fabric and its perfect geometric design is simply inviting. Pastel colors and soft curves give the capsule its cozy appeal, while the wood + powder-coated metal frames give it a stability without taking away from the softness. Sit in the Capsule and as your behind sinks into the cushion, you notice your peripheral vision getting narrowed. Its cocoon-esque design covers your sides and your top, blocking not just vision but also absorbing audio, leaving you in a tranquil bubble as you sleep, read, or work. A perfect chair/sofa set for someone who doesn’t want to make idle chit-chat and just wants to be!

Today I want to talk about a principle in UX called Occam’s Razor - -
---------------
---------------
🔪This Law States:
--------------
-------------
🤔 When presented with competing hypothetical answers to a problem, select the one with the fewest assumptions.
---
---
🚫 Now..
---
---
📱Some think this law has to do with simplification in the User Interface (UI). ---
--
----
⚠️That is a misconception
--------
--
❓It’s about choosing the simplest solution to a problem.
------------
----
🤚Hold up Miriam, you just said it’s not about simplifying???
---
---------
👌Okay, to clarify:

______
________
🔎1. Don’t go for the default solution, spend time researching the best UI pattern to use.
-
-
- Instead of using radio btns for 2 options, try using a switch
---
--
💻 2. Get out of Sketch! Think about your users mindset & jobs to be done
-
- Ride apps traditionally ask for your current location. But the user mindset is ‘I need to go somewhere’ How about we ask for the destination first?
---
---
📱3. Take into consideration how screens are getting bigger & challenge it.
-
- On desktop, the search bar is at the top. When going mobile we just copied this, no questions asked. The bottom of the screen has now become prime real estate, due to thumb reach. Let's bring 'search' down, using a iOS UI pattern - ‘bottom sheets’

_________
__________
🔲 There is simplification in terms of taking away elements or white space.
-
👉 Occam’s Razor is really about selecting the solution to a problem that is the simplest.

Cheat day with my #impossibleburger 🍔 I get asked a lot why I turned vegetarian (2 years strong now ✌🏻)... Well, I initially jumped aboard the meatless bandwagon for health purposes (I have a really sensitive tummy) and incidentally went aboard the environmental train! 
It’s nice to know that other than making a good difference on my body, I get to do the same for our earth’s sustainability 🌱

I won’t lie, it sucks to be a prune and not YOLO and enjoy a bigger variety of food with beloved company, but other than reaping health benefits, being a vegetarian has opened up my eyes to see and appreciate food in a very different light. 
With mindful effort, some inconvenience and a bit of creativity, there is SO much delightful and invigorating flavors to be discovered with plant-based foods. It’s comforting to know that more and more, kickass veggie options will be available and perhaps being known as a “vegetarian” won’t seem so much of a downer during social outings.

Also, I have a strong suspicion that my strangely thick hair now due to a massive drop in hair loss is from consuming less sodium long-term overall (meat contains a pretty healthy amount of natural sodium and on top of that, we still add salt to flavor it further).... my hairstylists can vouch for my newfound thick locks! 
If having more hair doesn’t change your mind, perhaps you need a visit to a slaughterhouse. Ignorance is still a sin, guys. Go plant-based la. Be good to your body and our earth. Peace fam ✌🏻 #vegetarian #leafeaters #gogreen #plantbasedfoods #savetheearth #makegreenmainstream #ecofriendly

This is what all digital products aim to do: Guide the user to make the right choices (easiest path), so they can complete their tasks. You can do this with visual guidance, Interaction design, UI elements, and I would especially highlight UX Writing. Usually UX Writing is the least important for product designers, yet, in general, 80% of the usability issues can be solved with better copy. This is mostly because language is the most natural and familiar connection you can create with your user.

MVP: Minimum Viable Product
It refers to a product development approach where the product is released when it has all the features to satisfy the early adopters. The final, complete set of features is only designed and developed after considering feedback from the product's initial users﻿. You can define the most valuable features by conducting research, and analysing the data with user journey maps and using the prioritization matrix. 
For a successful MVP you need to make a difference between what the user WANTS and what the user NEEDS
.

.

🎙5 TOP tips for Presentations:⁣
———⁣ .
➡️For more tips check #ux_tips_anfisign
.
.
⁣
1️⃣Connect with an audience⁣
———⁣
Before even starting a talk - Connect.⁣
Ask to raise hands people who also «experienced» it…Make them feel like you care and you’re here for them.⁣
⁣
💡People tend to get bored when they constantly have to read slides and listen to the topics they might not be interested. Make them a part of your story to raise an engagement.⁣
⁣
⁣
⁣
⁣
2️⃣ Storytelling⁣
———⁣ Picture is worth 1000 words.⁣
Add pictures that make YOU remember the point. It’s not only helpfll for you, but also the audience will connect with you better. They’ll not read while you’re talking, they’ll listen to you.⁣
⁣
💡You can remember the story and connect with it much faster than trying to read what you meant «here with that subtitle». ⁣
⁣
⁣
⁣
3️⃣Keep an eye contact⁣
———⁣
It’s scary, I know. You might get lost in your thoughts seeing so many eyeballs on you. But avoiding it can create «Tense». People want you to be open and look at them. So, imagine you’re talking to a friend. And doing at the beginning!⁣
⁣
💡Find someone who supports you from the begining. Focus on that person every time you talk to the audience. It’ll help you to stay confident.⁣
⁣
⁣
⁣
4️⃣Know your timing⁣
———⁣
Yesterday I gave a talk, but no one told me upfront how much time I’ll get. I’ve made slides for 50m talk. It appeared I had 30m.⁣
I’ve been talking really fast. Someone  even told me it was like 1.5x speed on YouTube.⁣
⁣
💡To avoid my mistake, ask right away from your organizers to provide you a clear brief and timing. Also, would be good if you practice your timing before an actual talk.⁣
⁣
⁣
⁣
⁣
5️⃣Stay positive⁣
———⁣
Q/A might seem to be the most stressful part for you, but only if you didn’t connect with the audience. If you did (if you’ve got an emotional response during a talk) - people will be excited to ask you more about it.⁣
⁣
💡Make sure to be relevant to this audience. If a developer talks to designers about his «design», there is a chance that designers would not get it. ⁣
⁣ ⁣

5 steps of UX Design

Define
A good place to start is asking yourself ‘What can we do to improve this problem?’. You’ll want to identify patterns, pain points, observe customer interactions, and use cases for that particular issue.

Research
After we gather all sorts of info on the problem, we need to start defining our customers. We should map out their social behaviors, demographics, motivations for using a product or service, and their expectations.

Analyze
Now is the time to put all of your ideas to a sketch board and let the creativity flow. Centered around this problem, no idea is off the table. This phase is about generating solutions to problems. 
Design
Concepting, wire framing, prototyping, and creating flows are completed in this step. The goal is to build and implement those solutions discussed in the first step and provide the high fidelity visuals for real-world feedback. 
Test
Here is where we get to validate our designs and research. We’ll gather feedback and analyze those results. If necessary, we’ll return to step 1 and repeat the process until Product Market Fit is achieved.

Every Step Counts⠀

- 8 Books for (User Interface) Designers 🔥
_
By: @lubosvolkov
__________
I would like to continue sharing more detailed design tips … The idea is to share with you the tips along with the practical visual examples … Let’s have a look at them.
__________
🧐 Why are books essential for a designer?
_____
The design industry is moving really fast … Learning new things is essential if you wanna stay up to date with the latest trends and best practices … Books can be an extremely valuable source of the knowledge … I have chosen a rich variety of books which will sharpen all your skills.
.
Design system tips
_____
1️⃣ Hooked: How to Build Habit-Forming Products
2️⃣ Don’t Make Me Think
3️⃣ The Paradox of Choice: Why More Is Less 
4️⃣ Type Matters!
5️⃣ The Designer's Dictionary of Color
6️⃣ Making and Breaking the Grid
7️⃣ Steal Like an Artist 
8⃣ Show Your Work
.
🤯 Key takeaways
_____
It is often hard to find to read a book … I recommend to set up milestones to read at least one chapter or few pages each day … Some books can give you extremely valuable knowledge or nice design inspiration … Just set some time aside for them each day or once a week. 
__________
➡️ Would you like to see similar tip posts like this more often? … No worries! I will keep sharing my other photos and designs!

➡️For more methods check #UX_methods
.
.⁣
One of the biggest challenges we, designers, always face is:⁣
❓How do we go from User research to Design Solutions?⁣
⁣
I’ve been stuck in this stage for a few times too.⁣
Luckily, to overcome this block, there are few Awesome exercises.⁣
They make the complex seem easy and straightforward:⁣
———⁣
1️⃣How Might We⁣
2️⃣Job Story⁣
3️⃣User Story⁣
———⁣
⁣
⁣
———⁣
1️⃣How Might We⁣
«Can we Solve it creatively?"⁣
⁣
❓What and Why?⁣
Brainstorming sessions to explore new wild ideas.⁣
It’s a perfect team activity focused on opportunities based on user insights.⁣
⁣
👇Tip:⁣
The word "might" allows the team to expand their thinking and include any possible solution to the problem. ⁣
⁣
⁣
⁣ ———⁣
2️⃣Job Story⁣
«What drives people to action?»⁣
⁣
❓What and Why?⁣
«Job stories» reframe the problem from:⁣
What do people want? 👉 Why they want it?⁣
⁣
👇Tip:⁣
Helps the team to understand the situation in⁣
which people encounter a problem and why it needs to be solved. ⁣
⁣
⁣
⁣ ———⁣
3️⃣User Story⁣
«See it from the users perspective.»⁣
⁣
❓What and Why?⁣
Framing a problem from the users perspective.⁣
Not the business, product, or technical perspective. ⁣
⁣
👇Tip:⁣
User stories should be written so that anyone could understand ⁣
the needs of the user without a technical understanding of the topic.⁣ ⁣
⁣

In the last couple of weeks I've worked with @morejanda , the author of Burn your portfolio. Great book by the way, check it out! We tried to define the meaning behind UX and UI design and the relationship between the two. Of course these two are broad categories, so we also focused on their main components. I think this turned out to be a great and simple visualization of what User Experience Design means. I'll share two more series from our collaboration in the following days but until then: Let's dig in!
.
⚫ User Experience Design (UX): The experience that a person has as they interact with a product. UX is an umbrella term that encompasses all of the other types of design to create a user’s experience with a company, product, or service.
.
⚫ User Interface Design (UI): The look and feel of a product designed to enhance the customer experience. UI is an umbrella term that encompasses all of the elements the make up the visual and tactile delivery of a user experience.
.
⚫ Content Strategy: Identification of content types and strategy to deliver them to a target audience.
.
⚫ Information Architecture (IA): The manner in which content is organized.
.
⚫ Interaction Design (IxD): The physical interaction a user has with a product.
.
⚫ Motion Design: Utilization of motion to enhance a user experience and delivery of content.
.
⚫ Visual Design: The visual representation of a content strategy and information architecture.
.

What tools do you use in your process? Let me know in the comments.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
I usually follow this UX process 👇🏼
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
1. Research
2. Structure
3. Wireframes
4. UI
5. Prototype 
6. Test
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
And I use the following tools for each step of the process:
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
—————————
1️⃣ Miro
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
I use Miro to collaborate and gather information from different sources.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
It’s like having a digital whiteboard, you can use it to create User Story Mapping, Mood boards, User Journeys, User Personas, etc., it helps me to have all the information that I need in one place.
—————————
2️⃣ Overflow
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Awesome tool to create beautiful user flows or Site maps.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
It syncs pretty well with Sketch which is great for my workflow. Also, you can use it to build flow charts and other types of charts. I also like that you can share your documents with clients easily with one link.
—————————
3️⃣ Sketch
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Sketch is the app that I use to create wireframes and the UI of every product.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
It allows me to create and easily maintain style guides, all the plugins created by the community around this tool is one of its biggest strengths. It also syncs pretty well with Overflow and Invision.
—————————
4️⃣ InVision + Studio
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
I use invision to build the prototype that is going to be tested with users.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
I also upload to Invision all the designed screens to receive feedback and I use Studio to make animations and clearly communicate ideas to developers which I think is very important.
—————————
5️⃣ Usertesting.com
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
User Testing is the tool I use to test the UI and get feedback from users.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
I like this tool because I can have feedback from users really fast, it is easy to set up and it let me target users from almost everywhere and uncover usability issues easily.

In the morning flocks of penguins gather on the beach before heading out to sea to feed. Kings aren’t picky eaters exactly but they’re very specific about what they hunt and catch. When the weather grows colder they eat more ice fish and cephalopds — molluscs, octopus and squid — to supplement their winter diet. Photo by @FransLanting “Happy Feet” Emperor penguin chicks are born on the feet of their parents. That’s where they crawl out of their eggs, which are kept off the ice by incubating adults, who cradle the eggs on their feet for two months. Here, a newborn chick sitting on its mother’s feet is getting a brief peek at the world before it gets covered again by a brood flap, which keeps chicks warm even under the extreme conditions emperors face during their reproduction cycle. If we can learn how to nurture our planet the way emperors take care of their offspring, we’ll all be better off. Photo by @FransLanting | Right now it is brutally cold and dark in Antarctica and yet emperor penguins are incubating their eggs. They huddle together in large groups to keep each other warm. It’s the only way they can survive the extreme conditions they face during their incredible reproduction cycle on the sea ice off Antarctica. During mid-winter blizzards, when males balance the eggs on their feet to keep them off the ice, temperatures can drop to -70 degrees. When I made this image I was standing on top of a platform perched at the edge of a colony and I had to stay still to avoid spooking the birds. It was an ordeal, and it took quite a while before I got warm again, but the images were worth it. Follow me @FransLanting and @ChristineEckstrom for more images and stories from the amazing world of emperor penguins. @ThePhotoSociety #Antarctica #Penguins #Extreme #Photography #Wildlifephotography #Cold

.
In the code, for the background animation, I've used the code from my previous tutorial on background gradient animation, you can check that tutorial at my page @therealamitk.
.
Background-clip property let's us make the background show only above the parameter specified. For example, when we set parameter as "text", the background of the div is clipped over the text in the same div. .

App design for one of my client! 
Basically this app about shopping online based on instalment. and I created this app from scretch using Whole study and UX UI Design.

Top tips before start UX Project 
1. Understand Requirment
Understanding the busines is key to solve business design problem, before understanding completly, DON'T START project.

2. Create UX Process
Every single have different approch and process to solve problems like redesign website or creating new app. Choose right approach accroding to time, budget and requirments.

3. User centred design
User center design is great way to approach and solve design for for end users. and you can start with Persona, User Stories, Secnarios (User cases).

Archie, 2017 
Fast is a relative term when photographing a puppy. I present Archie, a lightning fast Gordon Setter photographed at the ripe old age of 2 months.

I’m old and slow, working with cumbersome medium-format cameras where the odds of getting anything in focus are always against you. Archie likes to carefully track things way up in the trees or telephone poles. Things he can’t always get to unless they happen to be an old and slow photographer with a medium-format camera. 
#yearofthedogs is my ongoing personal project celebrating the beauty and character of dogs. 
If you enjoy this sort of thing, I’d invite you to follow my work @vincentjmusi

The post from the Australian Antarctic Division Facebook page has already been viewed over 85,000 times and shared over 1,000 times. 我覺得因為快樂並不在於擁有的多，而在於計較的少。而為什麼能計較的少?在於能把自己縮小到可以放在別人眼中和心中。至於為什麼要縮小自己呢？因為自己只能控制自己無法控制別人；那放的進別人的眼中跟心中有這麼重要嗎？因為己欲利而利人，己欲達而達人，所以別人快樂了自然可以一片和氣，自然自己也快樂了。這是生活的智慧😊

I’m honored to help people find their own by sharing my images & experiences in what’s has been called ‘America’s best idea’ .

Photo by @FransLanting After their first few weeks of life emperor penguin chicks are no longer brooded by their parents around the clock and they begin to form creches where they keep each other warm by huddling together, just like adults do in mid-winter. When parents return from the sea they head for the creches to pick up their chicks, which they recognize by sound rather than sight. In this image you can see two adults trying to figure out which of the chicks are theirs. Go to @FransLanting and @ChristineEckstrom to see more penguin huddles and if you are on the East Coast of the US we hope you’ll stay warm too, whether you can huddle or not!

She’s so cute, she meows hello, purrs nonstop, makes biscuits, rolls over for attention, wants all the head scratches, and licks and play bites.  She doesn’t want to explore the room yet so she’s just chilling in the crate, but she is so happy I can’t even believe it.  Now I don’t want her to be a winery cat anymore - I want her to live in a home.  So who wants to adopt my little flirt? @therescueteam

Red Panda. Despite its name, it’s not closely related to the panda. They do eat a lot of bamboo though! It makes up around 90% of their diet. Another similar trait with the panda – it has an enlarged wrist bone that acts kind of like a thumb which makes grasping bamboo easier. Red pandas are arboreal, meaning most of their time is spent in trees. Unfortunately, red pandas are listed as endangered by the IUCN. It’s estimated that they’ve lost 50% of their population in just the past two decades due to habitat loss and poaching among other reasons. .

In the heart of Chengdu you can find Du Fu's Thatched Cottage. This 24-acre park and museum was preserved in honour of the Tang Dynasty poet Du Fu. In 1961 the Chinese government established Du Fu Cao Tang as a National Heritage site. Du Fu is one of the most famous and beloved poets in Chinese history, he lived in the cottage with his family and composed 240 poems during his time there.  Inside the gardens are quiet; streams wind through the bamboo shoots and classical architectural styles bring you a strong cultural atmosphere.

One of my favorite things to do at Bryce Canyon National Park is to stand at one of the rim-top overlooks (Bryce Viewpoint, in this case) at sunrise or sunset with a long telephoto lens and pick out interesting features of the hoodoos to photograph. It's an exercise that could keep me happily occupied for hours on end, as the different shapes, textures, and formations of the hoodoos are infinitely fascinating to me. This sunrise was a particularly beautiful, windy, and frigid one. Bryce is up around 8000 feet in elevation and we were there in late November, which makes for freezing temps. But that doesn't matter...it is an amazing sight no matter when you go.

Bryce Canyon National Park (53 of 59)

Shot with FUJIFILM X-T1 and XF100-400 F4.5-5.6 lens

Creepily clever new painting from Casey Weldon @caseyweldon for his debut solo exhibition with Thinkspace. 'Sentimental Deprivation' is set to open this coming Saturday, June 3 with a reception from 6-9PM.
•
Weldon's works alternate between moments of intense darkness and incandescent light, figuratively and literally. Saturated with lush color and detail, they are stylized by idiosyncratic palette choices that capture a range of brightness and atmosphere, from the intensity of neon to the lambent of dusk and the recesses of twilight obscurity. The unexpected is always at play in the subject matter, as unlikely pairings, exaggerated spatial relationships, and incongruous contexts offer infinite possible realities and suggestive collusions. The world, delivered through the lens of Weldon’s imagination, is distorted on a hyperbolic visual plane, where the mythic proportions of incidental symbolism are laid open to the willing. Weldon creates works with hooks rather than imperatives, providing an openness to interpretation for the viewer rather than a prescriptive demand to be read.

Lions do not have the ability to sweat through glands, only through panting, which can make for some brutally hot conditions when you're neck and head are covered in thick fur. 六道
人類的存在，並不是唯一的業的景象。佛陀有提到有六種存在的界（稱為六道）：天、阿修羅、人、畜生、餓鬼、地獄。每一道都是六種主要煩惱的結果：驕傲、嫉妒、慾望、愚痴、貪婪、瞋恨。
這六道都確實存在嗎？它們也許存在於我們業的認知範圍之外。但千萬不要忘記：我們所看到的，是我們業的景象讓我們看到的，別無其他。就像在目前未淨化、未進化的認知狀態裡，我們只能察覺到自己的宇宙，而另一隻昆蟲也許會把我們的一隻手指看成整個山水。我們傲慢地只相信「眼見為真」，但偉大的佛法卻提到，在不同的面向有無數的世界-甚至有許多世界很像或就像我們的世界-而現在的天文物理學家已經發展出平行宇宙存在的理論。在我們有限的認知範圍之外，我們怎麼能夠肯定的說，何者存在或何者不存在呢？
看看周遭的世界，也看看我們內心的世界，我們能夠看到六道確實是存在的。它的存在方式，在於我們無意識地將煩惱投射出去，將環繞著我們的六道具體化，並且界定這六道當中的方式、形式、品味和內容。它們也存在於我們內心，在我們身心系統中，它們是各種煩惱的種子和傾向，隨著影響它們的因素和我們所選擇的生活方式，時時準備發芽成長。
讓我們看看六道如何在周遭世界裡投射和呈現。譬如，天道的主要特色是沒有痛苦，那是永不改變的美，以及極盡享受之能事的世界。想像天神的模樣：高大金髮的衝浪人，悠閒地斜躺在風和日麗的沙灘花園裡，聽著自己喜歡的音樂，沉醉在刺激物品裡，熱衷於靜坐、瑜珈、及雕塑身體等改善自己的功夫，只是從來不用腦筋，從來不曾碰到任何複雜或痛苦的情境，從來不曾意識到自己的真性，已經麻痺到不曾覺察自己到底真正是什麼樣子。
如果我們想起美國加州和澳洲的某些地區如同天道，你也可以看到阿修羅界每天都在華爾街的陰謀和競爭中，或在華盛頓和倫敦政府的喧騰走廊上不斷出現。至於餓鬼道呢？有些人儘管富可敵國，但從來不曾滿足過，渴望併吞一家又一家公司，永不休止地在法庭上表現他們的貪欲，這些人就是餓鬼道。打開任何電視頻道，你就立刻進入阿修羅和餓鬼的世界。
天道的生活品質似乎比人道好，但聖哲們說，人的生命價值卻無限可貴。為什麼？因為我們具有覺察力和智慧，這是開悟的素材；同時，人生無所不在的苦，可以激勵我們從事精神上的轉化。每一種痛苦、悲傷、損失和無止境的挫折，都有它真實而戲劇性的目的：喚醒我們，促使（近乎強迫）我們衝破輪迴，從而釋放被禁錮的光芒。
每一個精神傳統都強調，人身是殊勝的，具有我們未曾想過的潛力。如果錯過這一生轉化自己的機會，很可能要經過漫長時間的等待才能重獲人身。想像一隻盲龜，漫遊在宇宙這麼大的海洋深水裡，水面漂著一隻木環，在海浪間飄蕩。這隻龜百年才會浮上水面一次。佛說，生為人身比那隻盲龜浮上水面，又剛好把頭穿過木環還要困難。又說即使出生為人，有很大福氣得以接觸佛法的人更是稀有難得；而真正把佛法牢記心中，表現在行動上的人，就如白晝時的星星，寥寥無幾。

The iconic landmark of Lisbon, the Belém Tower, appears at night, but not as it usually looks! I was very fortunate on this evening as they turned off the lights on the tower for a few minutes for technical reasons. Otherwise capturing clear view of stars above this strongly lit monument is almost impossible! Constellation Taurus with the Pleiades star cluster and Jupiter (bright point) appear on the left above the 25 de Abril Bridge across the Tagus river (zoom in for details). The tower is a UNESCO World Heritage Site due to its significant role in the Portuguese maritime explorations in the 16th century. This fortified structure was a defense system at the mouth of the Tagus (Tejo) river, as well as a ceremonial gateway to #Lisbon. @natgeo @natgeocreative #cityscape #Portugal #Belém #worldheritage #nightsky #pleiades

巴西著名導演沃爾特·塞勒斯（Walter Salles）1998年在為電影「中央車站」選角的時候，挑選了很多藝校裡的學生，但都不夠滿意。 
有一天，為此一籌莫展的沃爾特到城市西郊辦事，在火車站的站前廣場上遇到了一個十多歲的擦鞋小男孩。
小男孩問道：「先生，您需要擦鞋嗎？」 沃爾特低頭看看自己腳上剛剛擦過不久的皮鞋，搖搖頭拒絕了。
就在沃爾特轉身走出十幾步之際，忽然見到那個小男孩紅著臉追上來，眸子裡現出祈求的眼神：「先生，我整整一天沒吃東西了，您能借給我幾個錢嗎？我從明天開始多多努力擦鞋， 保證一周後把錢還給您！」
沃爾特看著面前這個衣衫襤褸、瘦小乾癟的小男孩，不由得動了憐憫之心， 就掏出幾枚硬幣遞到小男孩手裡。小男孩感激的道了一聲謝謝後，一溜煙的小跑著離開了。
沃爾特搖了搖頭，因為這樣的街頭小騙子他已經司空見慣了。半個月後，沃爾特已經將借錢給小男孩的事忘的一乾二淨。
不料，在他又一次經過西郊火車站時，突然看到一個瘦小的身影離的老遠就向他招手 喊道：「先生，請等一等！」
等到對方滿頭大汗的跑過來把幾枚硬幣交給他時，沃爾特才認出這就是上次向他借錢的那個擦鞋小男孩。
小男孩氣喘吁吁的說：「先生，我在這裡等您很久了，今天總算可以把錢還給您！」
沃爾特看著自己手裡被汗水濡濕的硬幣，心頭陡然激蕩起一股暖暖的熱流。
沃爾特再次端詳面前的小男孩，忽然發現他很符合自己腦海中構想的電影裡那個小男孩主人公的角色形象。
沃爾特把幾枚硬幣塞進小男孩衣兜裡，說：「這點零錢就算是我給你的，不用還了。」
沃爾特接著又說：「明天你到市中心的影業公司導 演辦公室來找我，我會給你一個很大的驚喜。」
第二天一大早，門衛就告訴沃爾特說外面來了一大群孩子。他詫異的出去一看，就見那個小男孩興奮的跑過來，一臉天真的說：「先生，這些孩子都是和我一樣沒有父母的流浪孩子，他們也渴望有驚喜！」
沃爾特真沒想到一個窮困流浪的孩子竟會有一顆如此善良的心！通過反復觀察和篩選，沃爾特發現在這些孩子中，確實有幾個比小男孩更機靈，更適合出演劇本中的小主人公。
但他最後還是只把小男孩留了下來，並且在錄用合約書的「原因」一欄中寫下了這樣幾個字：「善良無須需考核，免試！」
因為他覺得這小男孩很善良，在自己面臨困境的時候，還願意把本屬於自己一個人的 希望，無私的分享給別人，這是怎樣的一種善良啊！而電影中的那個孩子，描寫的正是這樣一個善良、博大、無私的人。這個小男孩叫文尼斯基（Vinícius de Oliveira）。
在沃爾特的執導下，文尼斯基在1998年完成的巴西電影「中央車站」（Central do Brasil）中成功扮演了小男孩主人公的角色，也獲得柏林國際電影節、金熊獎等諸多桂冠。
若干年後，已成為一家影視文化公司董事長的文尼斯基寫了一部自傳 ─「我的演藝生涯」，在書的扉頁上面，是沃爾特的親筆題字：「善良無需考核」；下面則是他給予文尼斯基的評價：「是善良，曾經讓他把機遇讓給別的孩子；同樣也是善良，讓人生的機遇不曾錯過他！ 」

學習生存～
高山因為累積而厚重，大海因為容納而寬廣，樹苗因為風雨而茁壯，大道因為譭謗而高深，人類因為萬有而生存。
在成長過程裡，各適其所，各得其道，各依其緣而達到發展。
在生存過程裡有二條路，不是中斷，就是繼續；
選擇中斷的人，概已了無生趣，則無須贅言；
想繼續的人，就是已經掌握到生存方向。
因為種種而學會堅韌，因為種種學會放下，因為種種而學會不屈不撓；因為病痛知道了健康的可貴，因為破碎知道了圓滿的幸福。
生存為什麼可以漂亮？
因為堅定卓絕，義無反顧，猛然抽身，斷不猶豫，所以活得漂亮；行事坦然，與人坦白，樂觀上進，越挫越勇，所以活得自在；物質世界，情識妄慾，絕不掙扎，毫不沾滯，所以活得瀟灑。人人追求快樂，但不要忘記樂極生悲，這種快樂怕會流於放肆；喜悅與法喜也是一種快樂，但它本於寧靜，內中自有所得。
因此，細細的品嚐生存的美味，細細的品味生存的喜悲，能收能放，方不失修行本位。
生活可以如荊棘，可以如草原，讓心寧靜認真選擇，選擇之後不要徬徨，真誠以對，就是修行本格。

實現夢想的絆腳石
實現夢想的過程中有一個很重要的元素，也是一般人最難突破的關卡，就是要讓自己確定相信自己已經在願望達成的狀況，如果自己始終抱持的懷疑的態度，那吸引力法則的效果就會減弱，但是如果能夠突破自己矛盾的情況，而把自己心中的心境徹底轉變成為達到相信的境界，那將會無往不利。
吸引力法則究竟是不是真理或者定律並不是那麼樣的重要，重點在於這本書藉由吸引力法則傳遞了一個很重要的觀念：「努力」，常常我們在說天助自助者，書中並不是叫我們只要每天負責冥想就好了，而是要有所作為。當我們轉化信念選擇相信之後，就要立即的行動，才能享有豐碩的成果。
每個人其實都是一座寶庫，裡面蘊藏著無盡的資源。開啟寶庫的鑰匙不是父母、不是學校、也不是社會，而是我們自己。自己必須相信的是，愛能治癒一切的負面思想，而勇氣將打破所有的困難挑戰。
每個人都具有很強的能力、富有深厚的潛能，只不過現在還處於一種沈睡的狀態之中，倘若能夠喚醒，必能創造奇蹟。
關鍵三步驟
要求(ask)：對宇宙下命令，在心中許下自己的願望。 
相信(believe)：反覆確信自己的願望，是自己所要的，而且已經成真了。 
接受(receive)：擁抱自己的夢想，實際去感受吸引力法則的回饋。
吸引力法則沒說的事
許多朋友的吸引力法則其實都用錯了方法，舉一個很簡單的例子你就能夠明白。
當湯姆開車要去公司的路上，腦袋中頻頻想著「不會塞車」，但是一出門就遇到了車水馬龍的車潮，ＷＨＹ？因為當他腦袋中這麼想的時候，其實他只是運用了【表意識】，但實際上【潛意識】已經認為會塞車了，所以才會觸發了他腦袋中「不會塞車」的想法。如果你了解心理學，就會知道潛意識的能量是表意識的三萬倍，因此也就導致了出門塞車的結果。
了解為什麼很多人看完《秘密》之後，夢想卻仍舊無法達成的原因了吧！？ #親愛的朋友晚安 #連結內在的神性 #愛人如己❤️ #愛就完全了律法 #智慧的話語要用行動來理解 #智慧是平等心聰明卻是分別心 #吸引力法則✨

光芒內斂~
 一天上午，有一位父親邀他的兒子一同到林間漫步，他的兒子高興的答應了。
父子倆在一個彎道處停了下來。
在短暫的沉默之後，父親問兒子：「除了小鳥的歌唱之外，你還聽到了什麼聲音？」
兒子仔細的聽了幾秒鐘之後回答父親：「我聽到了馬車的聲音。」
父親說：「對，那是一輛空馬車。」
兒子驚奇的問他的父親：「我們又沒看見，您怎麼知道那是一輛空馬車？」
父親答道：「從聲音就能輕易的分辨出是不是空馬車。馬車越空，噪音就越大。」
後來兒子長大成人，每當他看到口若懸河、粗暴的打斷別人的談話、自以為是、目空一切、貶低別人的人，他都感覺好像是父親在自己的耳邊說：「馬車越空，噪音就越大。」
那些有渡河經驗的人，在涉水之前，總會習慣地抓起一塊石頭投入水中以估計水深。
水花濺得越高，河水也就越淺。
相反，那濺不起多大水花、聽不見多大水聲的地方必定深不可測……靜水流深，深水無聲。
馬車越空，噪音就越大。
不顯山，不露水，不虛張，想必做人，也該如此吧！
以此來品人和感悟人生，將會注意到以平心靜氣的口吻與別人的談話可以避免爭吵以及學會更多的傾聽別人的聲音，而不是一味的強調自己的主張。
舒特曼：「走急的人看不見地上的釘子，煩惱的人享受不到幸福的日子。」
雨果：世界上最寬闊的是海洋，比海洋寬闊的是天空，比天空更寬闊的是人的心靈。

Good Night

Wait for the guy who reaches for your hand on the street and holds it proudly. Wait for the guy who grabs your sides after stepping off the curb too soon.
Wait for the guy who reaches for you through the heavy mountain of blankets in the middle of the night, pulling you close.
Wait for the guy who slips out of bed as quietly as possible in the morning to shower, letting you catch a few more minutes of sleep.
Wait for the guy who almost always places his hand on your thigh – in the cab, on the train, on the couch, under the table at the restaurant. A simple gesture communicating everything.
Wait for the guy who makes the silence comfortable. Who builds your confidence. “Wear the shoes.” Who is passionate and takes his job seriously, yet still makes you a priority.
Wait for the guy who makes you laugh – genuinely laugh. A laugh that lasts far after the moment has passed, when happiness cannot be contained.
Wait for the guy who introduces you to friends and family with no fear.
Wait for the guy who never stops trying – pizzas with half pepperoni, home cooked meals eaten at the kitchen table, spur of the moment dinner plans, flowers – just because flowers, wine pit stops on the walk home after dinner, framed pictures, handwritten notes.
Wait for the guy who will continually put in the effort with your friends and family, knowing just how important they are to you.
Wait for the guy who you know will always say, “yes,” with no hesitation. Who sits across from you at the table and laughs to himself, telling you just how beautiful you are – and you believe him.
Wait for the guy who keeps his word-every single time.
Wait for the guy who never tires of forehead kisses. In the morning when your eyes are still closed. At night before he inevitably falls asleep and turns to his side.
Wait for the guy who shows up, no matter what. Who talks about your future without question.
Wait for the guy who makes you smile, because you knew through every bad date and lonely cab ride home, every ignored text message and every heartbreak, that patience and hope would lead you right to where you are right now.
Wait for it.
